00:00.972 --> 00:05.419
So here you can see examples of proteins and their high-level structure.

00:05.499 --> 00:12.951
So in these proteins what you call the primary structure is this sequence of amino acid.

00:13.111 --> 00:16.977
This is simply which amino acids are in which order.

00:16.957 --> 00:32.660
There is a thing called the secondary structures and we often observe that spans of these amino acids like substrings form these what are called these helixes as you can see here or these sheets.

00:33.842 --> 00:36.445
I don't know how they're strands in English.

00:37.467 --> 00:43.015
We call them sheets or I think these are the alpha helixes and these are the beta sheets.

00:42.995 --> 00:47.201
And there is also a turn, so I think this here might be a turn.

00:47.621 --> 00:59.698
So there are these kind of secondary structures, and then the tertiary structure is how this is still one protein, this is one unbroken chain of amino acid.

01:00.078 --> 01:06.707
And you can see this here kind of forms this double ring, which would be its tertiary structure.

01:06.687 --> 01:15.361
Very important for predicting the tertiary structure is to predict when two amino acids are close to each other.

01:15.561 --> 01:23.093
So if we have a chain right here and the chain as we saw before kind of turns and bends on itself,

01:23.073 --> 01:27.799
then these two amino acids here are very close in close contact.

01:28.641 --> 01:38.013
And to predict which amino acids are in close contact to each other helps you determine the tertiary structure.

01:38.094 --> 01:39.976
So that's a consequence of it.

01:39.996 --> 01:52.253
So we wonder, does BERT know intrinsically which of these amino acids are going to end up being in contact with each other without ever having been trained to do it?

01:53.448 --> 01:56.594
The second thing we're interested in are binding sites.

01:57.075 --> 02:09.178
So here, you might not be able to see, but we made this example before where this sort of forms a loop and then I say can trap something here, like another molecule.

02:09.158 --> 02:12.664
And this is what we would call a binding site.

02:12.744 --> 02:27.370
A binding site is a one amino acid that maybe through the structure of the surrounding amino acid as well, but also through its properties and how it is exposed in 3D shape,

02:27.350 --> 02:31.677
acts as sort of a receptor for other molecules.

02:31.837 --> 02:33.479
It binds to other things.

02:36.063 --> 02:42.073
So think of your hemoglobin that traps the oxygen in your blood or something like this.

02:42.714 --> 02:50.205
It is where a chemical reaction or a reaction with something else will happen.

02:50.265 --> 02:51.467
That's a binding site.

02:51.447 --> 03:02.854
And we are interested, does BERT, the BERT that is only trained on a language modeling objective know which ones are the binding sites?

03:02.954 --> 03:08.848
Because, you know, that would be very interesting and not something BERT was trained on.

